  <h1>Doha Expat Guide 2026: Salaries, Cost of Living, and Lifestyle</h1>

  <p>Doha is the capital and economic heart of Qatar, home to nearly 90% of the country's population and virtually all expat employment opportunities. Built on the wealth of the world's largest LNG reserves, Doha offers tax-free salaries, zero VAT, modern infrastructure built for the 2022 FIFA World Cup, and a compact, family-friendly lifestyle. For professionals in energy, healthcare, aviation, and education, Doha represents one of the most financially rewarding destinations in the Gulf. The city has transformed since hosting the World Cup, with world-class stadiums, a modern metro system, and upgraded roads and public spaces creating a living environment that balances Gulf wealth with genuine livability.</p>

  <div class="not-prose my-8"><CostOfLivingSimulator client:idle defaultCity="doha" /></div>

  <h2>Doha Salary Overview</h2>
  <p>The average expat salary in Doha is QAR 12,800 (~€3,200) per month, with significant variation by sector. QatarEnergy and its joint venture partners offer the most competitive packages in the country, with senior petroleum engineers earning QAR 30,000-45,000 (~€7,500-11,250) per month plus extensive benefits. Qatar Airways employs thousands of international staff, with pilots earning QAR 40,000-70,000 (~€10,000-17,500) and cabin crew QAR 6,000-12,000 (~€1,500-3,000). Hamad Medical Corporation, the public healthcare provider, recruits doctors at QAR 20,000-50,000 (~€5,000-12,500) depending on specialty. Qatar Foundation and Education City institutions offer strong academic packages. The banking sector, centered in Qatar Financial Centre (QFC), pays QAR 15,000-30,000 (~€3,750-7,500) for mid-to-senior financial professionals. All salaries are completely tax-free with zero social insurance deductions for expats.</p>
  <p>Further salary benchmarks for Doha in 2026: IT professionals earn QAR 12,000-25,000 (~€3,000-6,250), construction project managers QAR 18,000-35,000 (~€4,500-8,750), international school teachers QAR 10,000-18,000 (~€2,500-4,500), hotel managers QAR 14,000-25,000 (~€3,500-6,250), and accountants QAR 9,000-18,000 (~€2,250-4,500). Many Doha employers provide furnished accommodation or a housing allowance equivalent to 25-40% of the base salary, free annual flights for the employee and dependants, and end-of-service gratuity calculated at 21 days of salary per year of service. QatarEnergy compound living in Dukhan (the western oil town) is fully provided at no cost, with free housing, schools, recreation, and transport, making it one of the most financially advantageous postings in the global energy sector.</p>

  <CostOfLivingBreakdown city="Doha" country="qatar" />

  <h2>Cost of Living in Doha</h2>
  <p>Doha's cost of living benefits from Qatar's zero VAT policy, making everyday purchases cheaper than in the <a href="/uae/" class="text-brand-600 dark:text-brand-400 hover:underline">UAE</a> or <a href="/saudi-arabia/" class="text-brand-600 dark:text-brand-400 hover:underline">Saudi Arabia</a>. Housing is the largest expense: a one-bedroom apartment in The Pearl costs QAR 5,500-7,500 (~€1,375-1,875), while West Bay runs QAR 5,000-7,000 (~€1,250-1,750). More affordable areas like Al Sadd, Bin Mahmoud, and Al Mansoura offer one-bedrooms for QAR 3,500-5,000 (~€875-1,250). Family villas in compounds like Al Waab, Abu Hamour, or West Bay Lagoon cost QAR 10,000-20,000 (~€2,500-5,000). Groceries run QAR 1,000-2,000 (~€250-500) per month at Al Meera, LuLu, or Carrefour. Dining ranges from QAR 20 (~€5) at casual restaurants to QAR 140+ (~€35+) at mid-range venues. <a href="/qatar/utilities/" class="text-brand-600 dark:text-brand-400 hover:underline">Kahramaa utility bills</a> average QAR 300-800 (~€75-200) monthly. A single professional should budget QAR 6,500-9,500 (~€1,625-2,375) per month, while families need QAR 15,000-25,000 (~€3,750-6,250).</p>
  <p>Doha's zero VAT advantage adds up substantially over time. A household spending QAR 8,000 (~€2,000) per month on goods and services saves approximately QAR 400 (~€100) monthly compared to the UAE's 5% VAT and QAR 1,200 (~€300) compared to Saudi Arabia's 15% VAT. Over a three-year contract, that translates to QAR 14,400-43,200 (~€3,600-10,800) in additional purchasing power. Daily expenses include coffee at specialty cafes at QAR 18-30 (~€5-8), a fast-casual meal at QAR 25-40 (~€6-10), and a cinema ticket at QAR 35-55 (~€9-14). Gym memberships at Fitness First or local gyms cost QAR 200-400 (~€50-100) per month. Nursery fees for pre-school children range from QAR 15,000-30,000 (~€3,750-7,500) per year.</p>

  <h2>Neighborhoods and Housing</h2>
  <p>The Pearl-Qatar is Doha's premier residential island, offering a Mediterranean-style waterfront lifestyle with apartments, townhouses, restaurants, and retail. It is one of the few areas where non-Qatari nationals can purchase freehold property, which can support residency permit applications. Studios start from QAR 4,000 (~€1,000) and one-bedrooms from QAR 5,500 (~€1,375). West Bay is the business district with high-rise apartments and proximity to major employers including QatarEnergy, QFC, and government ministries, with rents of QAR 5,000-8,000 (~€1,250-2,000) for one-bedrooms. Al Sadd offers centrally located, older apartments at lower prices of QAR 3,000-4,500 (~€750-1,125), with good access to metro stations, restaurants, and Souq Waqif. Lusail City, built for the World Cup, is a new planned city north of Doha with modern apartments and family-friendly amenities including parks, a marina, and the Lusail Stadium area, with rents of QAR 4,500-7,000 (~€1,125-1,750). Compound living in areas like Al Waab provides villa communities with pools, gyms, and security, typically at QAR 10,000-18,000 (~€2,500-4,500) for a three-bedroom villa. Al Wakrah, south of Doha, offers budget-friendly options at QAR 2,500-4,000 (~€625-1,000) for apartments, with the Al Janoub Stadium area recently developed and connected to the metro Red Line.</p>
  <p>When choosing a neighborhood, consider proximity to your workplace and your children's school, as Doha's compact geography means most commutes are under 30 minutes. The Pearl and Lusail are ideal for families wanting a self-contained community with walkable amenities. West Bay suits single professionals who want to be near the business district. Al Sadd and Bin Mahmoud are best for those who prefer a more urban, multicultural environment with access to diverse dining options and the traditional Souq Waqif market. Rental contracts are typically annual, paid in monthly or quarterly installments via post-dated checks, and a security deposit of one month's rent is standard.</p>

  <h2>Commuting and Transportation</h2>
  <p>Doha's compact geography is one of its greatest advantages for expats. Most destinations within the city are reachable within 20-30 minutes by car. The Doha Metro, built for the 2022 World Cup and opened in 2019, operates three lines: the Red Line (north-south, serving Lusail and Al Wakrah), the Green Line (serving Education City and Al Riffa), and the Gold Line (serving key areas in central Doha). A monthly pass costs QAR 100 (~€25), making it among the cheapest metro systems in the Gulf. Single ride fares start at QAR 2 (~€0.50). Stations are modern, air-conditioned, and connected to dedicated bus routes through the Karwa bus network. Despite the metro, most expats own or lease cars due to the heat and the need to reach areas not served by the metro. Our <a href="/guides/driving-licence/" class="text-brand-600 dark:text-brand-400 hover:underline">driving licence guide</a> explains the conversion process for Qatar. Petrol is affordable at approximately QAR 1.80 (~€0.45) per liter. Car insurance runs QAR 1,500-3,500 (~€375-875) annually. Ride-hailing through Uber and Karwa Taxi is widely available, with typical inner-city fares of QAR 15-30 (~€4-8). The King Fahad Causeway to Bahrain was planned but not yet operational as of 2026; however, the Sharq Crossing bridge project continues to progress.</p>

  <h2>Working in Doha</h2>
  <p>Doha's job market is concentrated in several key sectors. Energy dominates through QatarEnergy and international partners including ExxonMobil, Shell, TotalEnergies, and ConocoPhillips, with the North Field Expansion project driving massive investment in LNG production capacity through 2030. Aviation centers on Qatar Airways, the national carrier with a global route network, employing pilots, cabin crew, ground staff, engineers, and corporate professionals at its headquarters near Hamad International Airport. Healthcare is led by Hamad Medical Corporation and Sidra Medicine, both actively recruiting international doctors, nurses, and allied health professionals. Education opportunities exist through Qatar Foundation, Qatar University, and numerous international schools, with Education City hosting branch campuses of Georgetown, Northwestern, Carnegie Mellon, Texas A&M, and Weill Cornell Medicine. The construction sector remains active with Lusail City completion and ongoing infrastructure maintenance. The Qatar Financial Centre hosts international banks, consulting firms, and professional services companies operating under a common law regulatory framework similar to DIFC in Dubai.</p>
  <p>The work week in Qatar is Sunday to Thursday for most organizations, though some international companies have adopted Monday to Friday. Working hours are typically 8 hours per day, reduced to 6 hours during Ramadan. Qatar's labor reforms since 2020 have removed the kafala system requirements, meaning employees can change employers without needing a no-objection certificate. The non-discriminatory minimum wage of QAR 1,000 (~€250) per month applies to all workers regardless of nationality. Qatarization requirements affect certain sectors, with quotas for Qatari nationals in government, banking, and some private sector roles, but specialist international positions remain widely available.</p>

  <h2>Schools and Education</h2>
  <p>Doha has a strong <a href="/qatar/education/" class="text-brand-600 dark:text-brand-400 hover:underline">international school network</a>. Doha College offers British curriculum education and is one of the oldest and most respected schools in the country, with fees of QAR 35,000-55,000 (~€8,750-13,750) per year. The American School of Doha follows a US curriculum with IB options at QAR 40,000-60,000 (~€10,000-15,000). Qatar Academy offers IB programs at several campuses under Qatar Foundation. Doha British School and Park House English School are popular British curriculum alternatives. For more affordable options, DPS (Delhi Public School) Modern Indian School, and other Indian-curriculum schools charge QAR 8,000-18,000 (~€2,000-4,500). Philippine, Pakistani, and other community schools also operate in Doha. School transport is available at most schools for QAR 3,000-5,000 (~€750-1,250) per year. Applications to top schools should be submitted 6-12 months in advance, as places at popular institutions fill quickly. For higher education, Education City provides exceptional opportunities without leaving Qatar, offering undergraduate and graduate programs from globally ranked institutions.</p>

  <h2>Healthcare</h2>
  <p>Doha has world-class healthcare. Hamad Medical Corporation operates 12 hospitals and is the primary public provider, with Hamad General Hospital serving as the main emergency and trauma center. Sidra Medicine, specializing in women's and children's health, is affiliated with Weill Cornell Medicine-Qatar and offers subspecialty pediatric and maternal care not available elsewhere in the country. Al Ahli Hospital and Aster DM Healthcare are top private options for routine consultations and minor procedures. The Qatar Council for Healthcare Practitioners (QCHP) regulates professional licensing and standards. Employer-mandated <a href="/qatar/healthcare/" class="text-brand-600 dark:text-brand-400 hover:underline">health insurance</a> covers most medical needs, including consultations, hospitalization, and prescription medications. GP visits typically cost QAR 100-300 (~€25-75) with insurance copay, while specialist consultations run QAR 200-500 (~€50-125). Pharmacies are widely available, and many over-the-counter medications familiar to Western expats are readily accessible. For emergency care, dialing 999 connects to the HMC ambulance service, which provides free emergency transport.</p>

  <h2>Social Life and Food Scene</h2>
  <p>Doha's social scene has expanded notably since the World Cup. Souq Waqif remains the cultural heart of the city, offering traditional markets, restaurants, art galleries, and live performances in a restored heritage setting. The Pearl-Qatar provides a Mediterranean-style promenade with international restaurants, designer boutiques, and waterfront dining. Katara Cultural Village hosts exhibitions, film screenings, concerts, and cultural events year-round, along with a private beach and amphitheater. The Museum of Islamic Art, designed by I. M. Pei, houses one of the most significant collections of Islamic art in the world, and the National Museum of Qatar, designed by Jean Nouvel, tells the story of the Qatari peninsula from geological formation to the present day. For dining, Doha offers everything from QAR 20 (~€5) shawarma shops to Michelin-recommended restaurants in West Bay hotels. The food scene includes strong Lebanese, Indian, Filipino, and Japanese cuisines alongside Qatari traditional dishes like machboos and harees. Alcohol is available at licensed hotel restaurants and bars, and residents can obtain a personal liquor permit through the Qatar Distribution Company (QDC) for home consumption, subject to employer approval and a minimum salary threshold. Weekend activities include desert safari trips (QAR 200-400 (~€50-100) per person), kayaking at Al Thakira mangroves, visiting the Khor Al Adaid inland sea (a UNESCO-recognized natural reserve), and beach time at Sealine or Fuwairit Beach. The tight-knit expat community organizes regular social events through groups like InterNations Doha, British Ladies Society, and various national community associations.</p>

